<body>
  <header>
    <h1>Black Sea ‚Äî a strategic chokepoint</h1>
    <p class="lead">Why this basin matters for trade, energy and security.</p>
  </header>

  <main>
    <article class="card">
      <section>
        <h2>What‚Äôs this about?</h2>
        <p>
          The Black Sea connects Europe, Asia and MENA grain and energy markets.
          Before the war, <strong>Russia and Ukraine</strong> jointly accounted for roughly
          <strong>34% of global wheat exports</strong>, <strong>17% of corn</strong> and
          <strong>~75% of sunflower oil</strong> (FAO). Disruptions to shipping and higher insurance premia
          transmit quickly into food prices.
        </p>
        <p class="pill">Source: FAO/FAOSTAT (shares)</p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Trade & food</h2>
        <p>
          In 2022‚Äì2023 the <em>Black Sea Grain Initiative</em> enabled exports of about
          <strong>32.9 million tonnes</strong> from Ukraine (mainly corn and wheat), which helped cool
          price pressure in global grain and vegetable oil baskets.
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Price channel:</strong> once shipping resumed, risk premia eased and MENA/EU access improved.</li>
          <li><strong>Supply chain:</strong> UA ports ‚Üí Bosporus ‚Üí Mediterranean ‚Üí MENA/EU ports (short route).</li>
          <li><strong>Insurance:</strong> tension lifts <em>war-risk</em> premia and banking requirements (LCs, sanctions clauses).</li>
        </ul>
        <ul class="sources">
          <li><a href="https://www.ifpri.org/blog/black-sea-grain-initiative-what-it-and-what-did-it-accomplish" target="_blank" rel="noopener">IFPRI ‚Äî what the Initiative was and achieved (~33 Mt)</a></li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Energy</h2>
        <p>
          The region also hosts energy infrastructure: Turkish fuel/LNG terminals and gas pipelines from Russia to TR/EU.
          <strong>TurkStream</strong> has a capacity of <strong>31.5 bcm/year</strong> (‚âà half to TR, half to EU via BG‚ÄìRS‚ÄìHU).
          With EU gas demand around <strong>~326‚Äì330 bcm in 2023</strong>, that‚Äôs a <strong>low-single-digit %</strong> share,
          yet important for transit states and regional consumers.
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Flows & policy:</strong> the Montreux Convention governs passage through straits; incidents raise risk.</li>
          <li><strong>Substitution:</strong> LNG and routes via TR reduce exposure to other corridors for parts of the EU.</li>
        </ul>
        <ul class="sources">
          <li><a href="https://turkstream.info/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">TurkStream ‚Äî official site (31.5 bcm/y)</a></li>
          <li><a href="https://www.iea.org/reports/gas-market-report-q1-2024" target="_blank" rel="noopener">IEA ‚Äî Gas Market Report Q1-2024 (EU demand ~326‚Äì330 bcm in 2023)</a></li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section class="wrap">
        <h2>What does it mean in practice?</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Food prices:</strong> resuming UA exports eased grain/oil indices; renewed disruption pushes them up.</li>
          <li><strong>Freight & insurance:</strong> NAVTEX/NOTAM warnings and incidents lift <em>war-risk</em> and freight rates.</li>
          <li><strong>Risk pass-through:</strong> shipowners/banks/insurers pass premia into final prices.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section class="cols">
        <div class="wrap">
          <h3 class="good">Upside / opportunities</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Higher capacity & predictability of routes (more stable prices, lower risk premia).</li>
            <li>Logistics diversification (TR, LNG, altern. routes) limits exposure to single chokepoints.</li>
            <li>Better coordination of trade finance & insurance (easier supply-chain financing).</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="wrap">
          <h3 class="bad">Downside / risks</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Step-ups in <em>war-risk</em> and freight after incidents; potential port stoppages.</li>
            <li>Eskalation can again restrict grain availability ‚Üí higher food-basket prices.</li>
            <li>Straits as chokepoints (Bosporus/Dardanelles) ‚Äî queues and delays in episodes.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Sources & further reading</h2>
        <ul class="sources">
          <li><a href="https://www.fao.org/3/cb9013en/cb9013en.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener">FAO ‚Äî Importance of Ukraine/Russia for global ag markets (wheat/corn/sunflower shares) ‚Äî PDF</a></li>
          <li><a href="https://www.ifpri.org/blog/black-sea-grain-initiative-what-it-and-what-did-it-accomplish" target="_blank" rel="noopener">IFPRI ‚Äî Black Sea Grain Initiative (~33 Mt)</a></li>
          <li><a href="https://turkstream.info/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">TurkStream ‚Äî technical parameters</a></li>
          <li><a href="https://www.iea.org/reports/gas-market-report-q1-2024" target="_blank" rel="noopener">IEA ‚Äî Gas Market Report Q1-2024</a></li>
        </ul>
        <p class="back">‚Üê <a href="/en/geopolitics.html">back to Geopolitics</a></p>
      </section>
    </article>
